[1] Brazil (Mato Grosso do Sul, Campo Grande)
Date: Fri 16 Oct 2009
Source: Campo Grande News [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.campogrande.news.com.br/canais/view/?canal=8&id=269912>


Dengue has now caused a death and the number of cases registered in
10 months, with 2 months to go before summer [2009], is up 213
percent from the total recorded in all last year [2008] in Campo
Grande. The statistics of ESAU (Municipal Secretariat of Health)
reinforces the alert issued by the prefect of the capital, Nelsinho
Trad, that, after swine influenza [A H1N1], the population must
redouble its concern for the disease caused [virus transmitted] by
the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.

From January [2009] up until this week, the municipality has
confirmed that 661 patients contracted dengue in Campo Grande. In
relation to last year [2008], when there were 211 cases, there has
been an increase [in the number of dengue cases] of 213 percent. Last
year's numbers included the rainy and hot season, which begins in
November. The number of people with DHF, the most serious and lethal
form, has exploded. There were 20 reported [DHF cases] this year
[2009], versus just one in 2008. Of these, 11 were confirmed. More
serious, one person died of dengue in May [2009], against no deaths
[in that period] last year.

Statistics now represent 50 percent of those [dengue cases]
registered in 2007, when there was an epidemic, with 2 deaths among
45 600 cases. This is to say that the disease is more lethal this
year, now that there has been one death among 213 confirmed cases.
[With just one death and a much small number of cases so far, it is
too early to conclude that the case fatality rate is higher, but
bears watching over the coming weeks. - Mod. TY]

[Considering] September -- the increase is much more significant if
one considers only the month of September [2009]. There were 36
confirmed [dengue] cases, an increase of 1700 percent over the 2
positive [cases] for the same period last year [2008].

Since June [2009], there was a decrease in cases of DHF. Only one
suspect [case] was reported in August. But the Health Department is
warning about the occurrence of the worst kind [of dengue disease],
especially in people who have contracted dengue fever before or have
some kind of disease such as diabetes, AIDS, heart problems, among others.

[Byline: Edivaldo Bitencourt]

--
