[2] Brazil (Mato Grosso do Sul, Dourados)
Date: Fri 16 Oct 2009
Source: Campo Grande News [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.campogrande.news.com.br/canais/view/?canal=8&id=269859>


The reported dengue cases have increased 483 percent this year
[2009], compared to the same period last year [2008], according to
the bulletin of the Epidemiological Surveillance Nucleus. From
January up to this week, 1006 people sought [attention at] health
facilities with symptoms of the disease. So far, at least 70 percent
of suspected cases have been confirmed, leaving Dourados as a
municipality with a high incidence of dengue. Another 45 cases are
still awaiting results of laboratory tests.

Most of the cases are classical dengue [fever], a less serious type
of disease. Meanwhile, public health has recorded 8 cases of dengue
with complications, including 3 children of less than 10 years.

According to the Epidemiological Surveillance Unit, the technical
evaluation of the cases shows that dengue affects mainly women (57
percent of confirmed cases) and is concentrated in the age group 10-49 years.

Despite the increase of almost 500 percent in relation to last year
[2008], public health verified the decline in the number of reports
in the last 2 months. The greatest period of the outbreak occurred in
the period March-August, with 939 suspected cases reported.

A detailed dengue survey showed that 19 neighborhoods in Dourados had
half of the [dengue] reports made this year [2009]. These same
neighborhoods have 62 percent of the confirmed cases.

[Byline: Helio de Freitas]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 9 Oct 2009 edition of Mato Grosso do Norte (in Portuguese,
