[3] Brazil (Mato Grosso, Rondonopolis)
Date: Wed 21 Oct 2009
Source: 24 Horas News [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.24horasnews.com.br/index.php?mat=308752>


The seasonality of the disease [dengue] is proven again. After an
outbreak of dengue in 2005, this year [2009] Rondonopolis is again
presenting very high levels of disease. Since the beginning of the
year [1 Jan 2009] through last Friday [16 Oct 2009], 837 dengue cases
of all types have been recorded, compared with 42 confirmed cases
during the whole of 2008.

From the beginning of the year [1 Jan 2009] up to last Friday (16
[Oct 2009]), 807 cases of classical dengue have been registered, 9 of
dengue with complications and 21 of DHF. In addition, this year 2
dengue deaths from DHF have occurred. According to the data from
SINAN [the national notifiable diseases information system], 760
cases were discarded [as dengue infections] and 28 were inconclusive
after the examination, that is, it was not possible to specify
whether or not there really was dengue [virus infection].

According to the coordinator of the municipal Public Health
Collective, Alencar Lebano de Paula, numbers are high because cases
were verified by virus isolation; the virus that circulated in the
city was [dengue virus] type 3 and earlier this year [2009] the
presence of types 1 and 2 [dengue] viruses was confirmed. Alencar
says that type 2 is more aggressive [virulent] and can lead to DHF.
"In April [2009] we verified that [dengue] virus types 1 and 2 were
circulating in the city. These same virus types were detected first
in Cuiaba and Varzea Grande, and since there is no physical barrier
between these cities, it [the viruses] arrived in Rondonopolis. There
will be a time when the people will be resistant [immune] to [dengue
virus] type 2 and we will not have so many cases of dengue," he explained.

In 2005, the municipality also registered a dengue outbreak, which
motivated the population to mount cleanup campaigns as well as
prevention measures, which has been done this year [2009] as well.

When professionals from the Municipal Health check a new case of
dengue they carry out the isolation of 14 blocks near the patient's
home, to prevent infected mosquitoes from passing along the disease
[virus] to other residents. The Secretariat works in accordance with
the National Dengue Control Program, according to regulations issued
by the Ministry of Health.

[Byline: Naila Albuquerque]

--
