[5] Nicaragua (Managua)
Date: Sat 17 Oct 2009
Source: Prensa Latina [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=126677&Itemid=10>


Dr Maritza Cuan, director of the Health Department reported today [17
Oct 2009] that Nicaraguan health authorities have increased their
preventive measures for the elimination of the causes of an increase
in [the number of] people affected by dengue. Now the fight is not
just centered on the mosquito vector, but also on the areas that
serve as reproduction [sites], pointed out Cuan. She added that
activities against the vector include not only abate [larvicide]
application and fumigation, but also collection of trash, which the
population discards in yards and waste places.

In the capital department [state or province equivalent] 853
classical dengue cases have been registered, 14 more than in the
previous day, 25 DHF [cases], and 5 deaths.

At a national level there are 1777 confirmed cases with 8 deaths,
with Managua heading the affected areas, followed by Masaya, Carazo,
Leon, Chinandega, Boaco, Chontales, Matagalpa, the South Atlantic
Autonomous Region, and Rio San Juan.

