[6] Venezuela
Date: Mon 19 Oct 2009
Source: El Universal [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://deportes.eluniversal.com/2009/10/19/pol_art_venezuela-tiene-once_1618462.shtml>



Venezuela has had a dengue epidemic for 11 weeks. Fumigation
campaigns have not given the results hoped for. Venezuela's dengue
epidemic has been going on for 11 weeks, as reflected by the Ministry
of Health in its epidemiological bulletin no. 38 of this year [2009]
(for 20-26 Sep 2009), which counts a total of 33 899 cases so far
this year, 2.7 percent less than those registered in 2008 for the
same dates (34 879 [cases]).

This official document, which came from the health office, indicates
that although there is a decline [in cases], this could be temporary,
due to the constant increase in the number of ill people reported in
the past 10 weeks. 736 cases registered from 12-18 Jul 2009 (week 38)
increasing to 1827 cases registered from 20-26 Sep 2009 ([week] 38).

The states with the greatest number of cases are Aragua
(3.948[cases]), Lara (3263), Barinas (3011), Zulia (2550), and
Monagas (2197). Other data that call attention are the deaths. The
regional epidemiological reports for the current year [2009] have
noted 7 dengue deaths: 3 in Lara, 3 in Aragua, and 2 in Carabobo. In
2008 the Ministry of Health did not register any deaths.

Up to 26 Sep [2009], the national administration has confirmed 2731
DHF cases, which represents 8.1 percent of the total [dengue]
illnesses. The incidence [ratio] between dengue fever/DHF is 18:1.

[Byline: Vivian Castillo]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
