[8] Dominican Republic
Date: Tue 20 Oct 2009
Source: Barrigaverde.net [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.barrigaverde.net/?q=node/5306>


The Secretariat of Public Health admitted that every day hospital and
private clinic admissions for dengue increase, but denied that an
epidemic exists, while just in the Robert Reid Hospital this Monday
[19 Oct 2009], 30 children were admitted for this disease. The dengue
admissions in assistance centers are increasing, which worries the
secretary of health Bautista Rojas Gomez.

However, the official denies that a dengue epidemic exists in the
country, despite that more than 3400 cases and 26 deaths from this
disease have been reported.

Meanwhile the Hospital Robert Reid's demand for assistance for dengue
is increasing and this Monday [19 Oct 2009] they had admitted 30
children, as the director of this health center, Emilio Mena Castro,
reported. Ill people continue to arrive from San Cristobal, Bani, and
neighborhoods in the capital, while many mothers agree that it is
necessary to eliminate mosquito breeding sites.

What most worries experts in dengue management is that the disease is
complicated by other viruses, which increases the risk of death in
the country [Which other viruses? Other dengue virus serotypes? - Mod.TY]

It is estimated that in the months of November and December, as has
occurred in previous years, the [number] of dengue cases will
increase even more.

[Byline: Javier Peguero]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The secretary of health's refusal to call this an epidemic is,
perhaps, a semantic problem. In any event, the Dominican Republic is
experiencing a dengue outbreak with thousands of cases with the risk
of increases near-term.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Dominican Republic can
