[10] Bangladesh (Dhaka)
Date: Fri 16 Oct 2009
Source: The New Nation [edited]
<http://nation.ittefaq.com/issues/2009/10/16/news0834.htm>


Late and prolonged monsoon in the country has led to a sudden rise in
the number of dengue patients, prompting fears of an outbreak of the
disease in the capital.

Dengue fever, transmitted by the _Aedes_ mosquito, is associated with
monsoon rains, usually from July to September. However, officials
said they had seen more cases in hospitals and clinics this year
[2009] compared to the previous years.

Symptoms of dengue include fever, joint pain, nausea and piercing
headaches. Dengue haemorrhagic fever, a potentially fatal form that
causes internal bleeding and circulatory failure, is most common in
children under 15, but it also occurs in adults. No vaccine is
available yet and there is no specific treatment. So dengue control
is primarily dependent on control of the _Aedes_ mosquito.

Shah Monir Hossain, director-general of the Directorate General of
Health Services (DGHS) told the reporters that the number of dengue
patients has suddenly gone up. "We don't have any figure of the exact
number of patients, but reports from the public and private hospitals
and clinics suggest that number of dengue patients has been on the
rise since Eid," he said. [EID is a Muslim holiday that marks the end
of Ramadan, the Islamic holy month of fasting. - Mod.TY]

Meanwhile, Dhaka City Corporation (DCC) mayor, Sadeq Hossain Khoka,
said that as of 1 Oct 2009, a total of 405 dengue patients had been
admitted to hospitals and clinics in Dhaka.

Health officials have urged people not to panic, citing the capacity
of the health service to deal with the disease. However, city
dwellers have criticised the DCC for clogged sewers and poor mosquito
control, prompting the mayor to announce a massive city cleanliness
and awareness raising campaign on 3 Oct [2009]. [Clogged sewers,
although a public health risk for other reasons, are not the problem
contributing to _Aedes_ dengue virus vector mosquito populations --
water catchments in houses and building are, something that the
residents of these buildings can do something about to eliminate, if
informed. - Mod.TY]

Health workers have reported 5 or 6 new cases daily at each of the
hospitals and clinics, but NGO workers warned that the number of
people with dengue would be much higher in the city's congested
slums. The situation might worsen in the next few days, as the hot,
humid conditions will help breed more mosquitoes, medical sources said.

A dengue outbreak in Bangladesh in 2000 infected over 5000 people and
93 died, while over 6000 were infected and 58 died in 2002, according
to WHO figures.

[Byline: Mamunur Rashid]

